  <div class="ct">
  
<p>.. former State Senate President John Andrews</p>
<p>And I'm wondering if this focus actually helps the republicans with their con job in some ways.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.squarestate.net/diary/2764/columnist-cant-cite-evidence-to-support-assertion-that-electionday-registration-favors-dems">Columnist can't cite evidence to support assertion that election-day registration favors Dems:</a></p>
<blockquote>So, I asked Andrews, your view is based on your experience here in Colorado?
<p>Yes, he said, along with his trust in Secretary of State Scott Gessler and former State Sen. Mark Hillman, who share Andrews' "alarm."</p>
<p>If you talk to Andrews repeatedly, as I have over the years, you know that he usually takes a conversation about a slice of public policy, like election-day registration, and broadens it to discussion about human motivations or political philosophy. It's fun, but sometimes it scares you.</p>
<p><strong>In this case, Andrews said he doesn't think Colorado should go to "great lengths to turn everybody out to vote."</strong></p>
<p><strong>"People who demonstrate what economists call 'rational ignorance,' I don't want those people voting,"</strong> he said.</p>
<p>"I'm a believer that voting should be more deliberative."</p>
<p>Democrats, he said, are more inclined to be "emotional" about a political campaign or "snowed by an ad campaign," while Republicans, he says are more "fact-based."</p>
<p>Thus he believes election-day registration favors Democrats, and my point that there no evidence to support his position didn't seem to bother Andrews at all.</p>
</blockquote>
Because it's been well documented that <a href="http://thinkprogress.org/justice/2012/11/06/1149211/colorado-secretary-of-state-under-investigation-for-taxpayer-funded-trip-to-gop-voter-suppression-meeting/">Scott Gessler</a> doesn't believe that everyone has the right to vote - <a href="http://www.commoncause.org/site/pp.asp?c=dkLNK1MQIwG&amp;b=7767089">not really</a>.
<p>So refuting whether early voting helps Dems is actually kind of giving a pass to the voter supressors Scott Gesslers/Andrews.<br />
&nbsp;It allows the story to be about early voting and whether it favors Dems over republicans.</p>
<p>It's not about favoring it's about hurting imo.</p>
<p>The larger story is that cutting out early voting is just one of many tactics to disenfranchise certain voters - Dems - and more often than not that means minorities.</p>
<p><strong>Otoh:</strong> Jason Salzman is responding to an absurd unproven assertion [lie] by Andrews and may have covered voter suppression already in other stories, and I'm only seeing one small piece of his work today.</p>
<p>I've been learning bit-by-bit to recognize trends in the way things are framed that overlook and even aid the conservative agenda, even when that is NOT the intent.</p>
<p>Nice weekly round-up MB</p>
